caption.text:
Today marks my first full year of sojourn. 
Embarking for the land I had only visited 14 years earlier was a pivotal life decision. My initial longing for that epitomical American life flew aside as the plane ascended -- gone were those pampered utopian thoughts. So much happened afterwards. So many windows were opened, enlightening my viewpoints. So many ceilings were lifted, redefining the reach of possibilities. But the dropping of those protective barriers also left me unsheltered to unforgiving circumstances. Nevertheless, I am forever grateful to my family, who has been supporting me incessantly, and I long to be reunited again.

Dr. Sun Yat-sen, the promulgator of the Revolution and later known as the Father of Republican China, had shoveled enormous sums of financial aid from the Overseas Chinese throughout his 17-year exile for the Revolution's cause. A normal routine within the contemporary school life would most likely include getting up - despite the magnetic attachment towards the "heavenly surface" - at dawn, being hypnotized by the classroom's humdrum aura of intricate theories and succumbing to the bagful load of assignments and exams, worthy of depriving the adequate hours of sleep. Yes, I have endured all of that, at least for the past six years at this particular place. 
Yet as I reminisce my times of strolling through those narrow corridors and spacious grounds, with each corner treasuring the memories of a roller-coaster journey, I can simply put that the experiences I have endured at this den were more than that of the ordinary routine. 
The stress, the laughter, the uncivilized behavior showcased - these are only a few of the colors of my vibrant secondary school life. 
No way, I'm actually graduating tomorrow.
